<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-05-07T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-05-07T03:00:00-05:00" n="78" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d78">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/4308: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Ethiopia</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Engert</hi></persName>)
                                    <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Addis
                                            Ababa</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-05-07T11:00:00+03:00">May 7, 1936—11
                                    a.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 7—10:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>305. Detachment of about 50 French Senegalese troops arrived
                                yesterday from Djibouti to guard railway station but left today as
                                no longer needed. Five hundred have been at Diré Dawa for several
                                days and have received instructions to prevent all rioting when
                                Ethiopian authorities depart. Harrar is expected to be in Italian
                                hands in a day or two.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>